\pard\qc\sa240\b\f1\fs34 MorphIQ Final Master Plan\b0\par
\pard\qc\sa180\i\fs24 Execution plan to take MorphIQ from current audited state to a production-ready platform for five letting agencies\i0\par
\pard\sa120\fs22 Prepared on 6 April 2026 for the MorphIQ Product project.\par
\pard\sa120\fs22 This document combines the diagnostic audit summary, target operating model, execution roadmap, technical checklist, security checklist, client onboarding checklist, launch checklist, and definition of done so the remaining work can be executed systematically.\par
\pard\sa160\b\f1\fs28 1. Executive Summary\b0\par
\pard\sa120\fs22 I completed a read-only diagnostic audit of the current MorphIQ codebase, portal, database, authentication layer, pipeline components, templates, issue markers, and git state. I verified that the project root is Desktop\\\\MorphIQ\\\\Product, that portal.db and .env both exist, that the portal Flask app is live in portal_new/app.py, that the scan pipeline files exist, and that the project is already beyond prototype stage.\par
\pard\sa120\fs22 The audit confirmed that the current database contains 17 clients, 218 properties, 460 documents, 1614 document fields, 2 users, 1 pack, and 24 compliance actions. Authentication is implemented using Flask-Login, with a users table, login and logout routes, a current-client helper, and login protection on most routes. The pipeline integration from auto_ocr_watch.py into sync_to_portal.py is present, which means the OCR to AI prefill to portal sync flow is structurally connected.\par
\pard\sa120\fs22 The same audit also found important gaps that must be closed before client onboarding and production launch: some sensitive routes are not fully protected, some mutations are not fully tenant-scoped, there are legacy path references to C:\\\\ScanSystem_v2 in a few places, there is leftover debug logging, there are duplicate or stale templates, and the current architecture is not yet packaged as a production-grade platform with agency isolation, operational controls, backups, monitoring, deployment automation, and client support processes.\par
\pard\sa120\fs22 The target state for this master plan is a platform that can support five separate letting agencies, where each client has isolated access to its own data and users, no client can ever access another client's data, and super-admin users can access all clients in a controlled and auditable way. The platform must work both locally on Windows for operations and on a Hetzner VPS for production.\par
\pard\sa120\fs22 This master plan assumes a go-live standard where a real customer can be onboarded without manual firefighting. That means the system must be secure, testable, recoverable, documented, observable, backed up, and operationally supportable, not just coded.\par
